| Because you don't know ahead of time whether it will be used or not.

Yes, but -- that is the same fallacy the just-in-time people fall victim all
the time.  *If* you execute it at some point you *will* pay for it at some
point. There is (still) no free lunch.

I like the predictability of 'paying' that price ex ante.  Templates are very
strong manifestation of that approach too: spend cpu cycles at compilation
time so that you don't have to at run-time.

Anyway, this is massively off-topic.  Do play with Promises if it suits you...

